I cannot write the entire program for you, but I can provide you with a basic C++ example using standard library functions and `string` manipulation. This example assumes you're looking for the occurrences of a specific word called "apple". You'll need to replace "apple" with your target word.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string filename = "input.txt";
    std::string target_word = "apple";
    std::string line;
    size_t count = 0;

    std::ifstream file(filename);

    if (file.is_open()) {
        while (getline(file, line)) {
            size_t pos = 0;
            while ((pos = line.find(target_word, pos)) != std::string::npos) {
                count++;
                pos += target_word.length();
            }
        }
        file.close();

        std::cout << "The word 'apple' occurs " << count << " times in the file.\n";
    } else {
        std::cerr << "Unable to open file: " << filename << '\n';
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This program reads the file line by line using `getline()`, searches for occurrences of the target word within each line using `find()`, and keeps a count. If the file cannot be opened, an error message is displayed. Make sure to replace "input.txt" with the path to your actual text file.

Keep in mind that this example is case-sensitive, so it will only count occurrences of the target word if it appears exactly as given (in lowercase "apple" in this case). If you want case-insensitive searching, you can convert both the line and target_word to lowercase before comparing.

Here's an updated version with case-insensitive searching:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string filename = "input.txt";
    std::string target_word = "apple";
    size_t count = 0;
    std::string line;

    std::ifstream file(filename);

    if (file.is_open()) {
        while (getline(file, line)) {
            size_t pos;
            std::transform(line.begin(), line.end(), line.begin(), ::tolower); // Convert line to lowercase
            pos = line.find(target_word, 0); // Search from the start of the line
            while (pos != std::string::npos) {
                count++;
                pos += target_word.length();

                // Search from the next position in the line
                std::transform(line.begin() + pos, line.end(), line.begin() + pos, ::tolower);
                pos = line.find(target_word, pos);
            }
        }
        file.close();

        std::cout << "The word 'apple' occurs " << count << " times in the file.\n";
    } else {
        std::cerr << "Unable to open file: " << filename << '\n';
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This version converts the entire line to lowercase before searching for occurrences of "apple", ensuring case-insensitive matching.
